The good news is: you can fully control this, and Playwright gives you the hooks to do it cleanly.

Let me walk you through the right way to make every video traceable.

🎥 How to know which test a video belongs to
The key is:
You must rename or relocate the video file after the test finishes, because Playwright only gives you the final video path once the test ends.

In Java Playwright, you do this by:

Getting the test name from TestNG

Getting the browser name from the context

Getting the video file path from Playwright

Moving the file to a deterministic location

✅ The correct pattern (high‑level)
1. Start video recording in PlaywrightManager
You configure the context like:

java
BrowserContext context = browser.newContext(
    new Browser.NewContextOptions()
        .setRecordVideoDir(Paths.get("videos/raw"))
        .setRecordVideoSize(1280, 720)
);
2. After the test finishes, retrieve the video file
Playwright exposes:

java
page.video().path();
This gives you the actual .webm file.

3. Rename + move the file using your own naming convention
For example:

Code
artifacts/videos/{browser}/{testName}/{timestamp}.webm
This guarantees uniqueness and traceability.

⭐ Recommended naming convention
A rock‑solid pattern is:

Code
{testName}__{browser}__{dataSet}__{timestamp}.webm
Examples:

Code
LoginTest__chrome__validUser__2026-03-28T21-05-12.webm
LoginTest__firefox__invalidUser__2026-03-28T21-05-13.webm
CheckoutTest__webkit__guestUser__2026-03-28T21-05-14.webm
